> 	Why aren't both haves 80 bits, and need to be XORed together to
> work, so that 1 key part doesn't help?  Apart from mindless speculation
> about the NSA wanting to read things, what reason would there be for
this
> kind of decision?

Umm, I don't know how to say this, but this is how the keys are broken up.
It's gets reported as two 'halves' in the media so your average person
can understand, even though it's inaccurate.
 
> 	Also, why 80 bits instead of 128?  (A more convenient number for
> modern computer software people)

Good question;  care to make a guess at how many bits the NSA can
brute-force?

